Music-Evoked Autobiographical Memories (MEAM)

Simply put — it's when a song brings back a personal memory and the feelings that came with it.
For example, if you heard a certain song a lot as a child at home, hearing that same song years later can instantly bring back the feeling of being there — the safety, the warmth, the people around you.
The brain stores music together with the emotions and memories from the moment you first heard it. So the song becomes like a shortcut back in time — not just remembering the moment, but actually feeling it again.
This is why music is so powerful for people with dementia — even when most memories are gone, these deeply stored music-emotion connections often remain intact.
